post_text:
The USDA has issued a waiver allowing all children ages 1 to 18 to eat free at the school cafeteria until December 31st. All students at WPS will be offered both breakfast and lunch for free until this program runs out. Students who are on the distance learning plan can continue to pick up lunches from 11 to 12:30 at the west Middle School doors. If you are not on sight but plan to eat please contact Christie Brewer (580-623-7361) at the Middle School office by 8:30 AM so that enough meals are prepared.

Please note that this does not remove the requirement for filling out the household lunch application. Many of our other programs are based on these applications.

post_text: Attention parents, DVAP-marked absences do NOT count as an absence with Watonga Public Schools. It is simply the State Department of Education‚Äôs way of the school communicating to the state that students are present virtually. We realize that it is showing as an absence, but that absence simply means that the student is not physically present in the school building. Again, it does NOT count as an absence as far as Watonga Public Schools is concerned. When we return to in-person school, the DVAP and DVA will go away.

post_text:
We at WPS will be amending our county color based policy and allow extracurricular activities to continue as normal. We realized that the numbers that rose and placed Blaine county in the orange were due to other areas. Local numbers remained at the same level as the prior week.
We are working on a revised plan that will be based on local numbers that we feel are more relevant to our decisions. We appreciate your patience. We will continue to evaluate our decisions and try to keep our students safe while also trying to allow them as many opportunities as we can.

post_text: Today marks what would have been the graduation ceremony for the class of 2020. Seniors, congratulations! Not only did you achieve this accomplishment, but you did so with resilience through one of the most unexpected challenges of your generation. We could not be more proud of you all. The future is yours now. Our greatest hope is that you believe in yourself, pursue your dreams, and never stop learning. This is just the beginning, and we are so excited to see where the next chapter leads you. We can‚Äôt wait to see you all again on June 6th for the official graduation ceremony, but, until then, Congratulations Graduating Class of 2020! You did it!

Joy Hofmeister

post_text: Grab and Go Lunches!!! 11 AM-1 PM
shared_text:
Tara Bomhoff is with Christie Brewer and 3 others.
March 30 at 8:54 PM ¬∑

Hey all you cool cats and kittens! Don't forget our Watonga lunch crew is still working hard Monday-Friday to get these babies fed! Those hard working folks have been making over 400 lunches and 400 breakfast a day with a skeleton crew. Not easy at all. They don't get all the glory they deserve. So shout out to those in back who are busting their tails for our kids.

Details:
ü¶ÖGrab and go at the Watonga Middle School, 4th and Clevenger and at Grand Prairie apts from 11am-1pm.
ü¶ÖBreakfast/lunch in a to go bag.
ü¶ÖIt is limited but if you can't make it up to any location, send me a message and I or someone will take care of you.
ü¶ÖIt is free for all 18 and under.

post_text:
These four Watonga Elementary students participated in the Elks‚Äô Hoop Shoot this morning at Lomega High School which started at 9 AM. They were there by 8 AM warming up. (The gym was super cold!)

They competed against other students their age from the communities of Okarche, Lomega, Holy Trinity School, Kingfisher, and Okeene. Trey Betancur and Cherish Brewer competed in the 8 & 9-year-old age division. Sam Miller and Caybre Wilson competed in the 10 & 11-year-old age division.

Trey won a 3rd place trophy hitting 15 out of 25 in regulation and 3 out of 5 in a shootout. üèÜüèÜ

Sam won a 2nd place trophy hitting 16 out of 25! In the event the 1st place winner can‚Äôt compete in the next round of the competition, Sam will step in and take his spot. üèÜ

They all competed hard and tried their best! They represented Watonga well, and their instructor Mrs. Ross, who was there with them, was proud of them. Coach Graham and I were proud of them too!!

Great job Little Eagles! üèÄü¶Ö‚ô•Ô∏è

post_text: Mrs. Kalicki‚Äôs 5th grade home room was selected to attend the Governor‚Äôs Christmas Tree Lighting Ceremony yesterday at the Oklahoma History Center. It was a fun and busy day!! It started with decorating their own tree and taking in dance, art and some of the museum. They then took pictures with Representative Sanders, Senator Jech, Governor Stitt, State Superintendent Joy Hofmeister and of course Santa. They did a few arts and crafts and closed the day with the tree lighting. They represented Watonga very well, and we are so glad they had this opportunity!

post_text:
Watonga Elementary School will be hosting our Back to School Enrollment August 5& 6!!! Enrollment is required for ALL students, returning and/or new! Times for enrollment are as follows:

Aug 5: 2pm-6pm
Aug 6: 9am-1pm

***Requirements for pre-K enrollment and new students are: birth certificates, social security card, immunizations, proof of residency (i.e. utility bill valid within 30 days), Parent/guardian ID and Certificate of Indian Blood (CDIB) if applicable. Please note, State Law prohibits us from accepting school enrollment applications that do not have updated immunization records.

If you have questions, please feel free to call the office, 580-623-5248.

We also want to welcome everyone to our Back to School Night to be held on Aug. 13 from 5pm-6:30pm!

UPDATE 11/27/18 3:40 P.M. City of Watonga: We are working to restore water now. Per Oklahoma DEQ guidelines, once the water is restored you MUST bring water to a boil; then allow it to cool for drinking. You will need to boil the water until our water passes testing from DEQ. We will be posting updates on this page as well as on the bank marquees and the newspaper. Please share and thank you for your patience.

Bottled water will be provided for students tomorrow.

https://www.ok.gov/health2/documents/Safe%20Water%20During%20a%20Boil%20Advisory%202008.pdf

post_text: The Elementary School has been working to help fight hunger in Blaine County for the last two weeks. We were in a little competition with surrounding school districts to try and collect the most food by weight for our county food drive. We won the competition by collecting 1,460 pounds of food!!! The support from our students and community was overwhelming!!! All of the food collected goes directly to our local food bank! Way to go Eagles!!!

post_text:
Mrs. Gorman worked with our 4th graders this week in the library completing the ‚ÄúPenny Raft Challenge‚Äù. The students read a story in class, and then created a raft with drinking straws, rubber bands and tape. Students tested the durability of their rafts by placing pennies onto the raft until it would no longer float! The first place raft was made by Isaac Sanders,
Addi Cole, Logan Kelly, Michael Black and
Joshua Brewer. Their raft held 26 pennies! Screeching in at second place was a raft made by Kinze Cowan, James Lockhart, Kadence Hutchinson and Gabe Lowry. Their raft held 25 pennies! The third place raft was created by Wade Manke, Chazz Tallboy and Mathan Carmichael. Their raft held 17 pennies!!! Great job 4th grade!!
